      {
        "type": "regex",
        "pattern": "(?i)(?:Driver\\s*=\\s*\\{[^}]*SQL Server[^}]*\\}|DRIVER\\s*=\\s*\\{[^}]*SQL Server[^}]*\\})[^\"';]*(?:Pwd|PWD|pwd|Password|PASSWORD|password)\\s*=\\s*(?!\\{|\\$\\{|<)([A-Za-z0-9!@#$%^&*()_+=\\[\\]|:,.<>?/\\\\~-]{8,50})(?![}>;])",
        "message": "SQL Server ODBC connection string with embedded password detected - CRITICAL. ODBC connection strings with password/pwd parameters (Driver={SQL Server};Server=...;Pwd=xxx) expose SQL Server authentication credentials directly. This format is commonly used in legacy applications, reporting tools (Crystal Reports, SSRS), ETL processes, and data integration platforms. Exposed credentials provide full database access including data exfiltration, modification, deletion, and potential server compromise. IMMEDIATE ACTIONS: 1) Remove password from ODBC connection string, 2) Rotate SQL Server login credentials immediately using ALTER LOGIN, 3) Implement secure alternatives: Windows Integrated Authentication (Trusted_Connection=Yes), DSN (Data Source Name) configurations with encrypted passwords, Azure Active Directory authentication, or connection string encryption, 4) Review SQL Server audit logs and Extended Events for unauthorized access patterns, 5) Update ODBC driver to latest version with enhanced security features, 6) Implement connection pooling with secure credential storage, 7) Use SQL Server roles and permissions following least privilege principle.",
