      {
        "type": "regex",
        "pattern": "(?i)(?:sql_server|sqlserver|mssql|ms_sql)[_\\s]*(?:password|passwd|pwd)[\"'\\s]*[:=][\"'\\s]*(?!\\{|\\$\\{|<|os\\.|\\[)([A-Za-z0-9!@#$%^&*()_+=\\[\\]|;:,.<>?/\\\\~-]{8,50})(?![}>;])[\"';,\\s\\)]",
        "message": "SQL Server password variable detected in source code - CRITICAL. Hardcoded SQL Server database passwords in source code expose authentication credentials that can be easily discovered through code review, version control history (git log, git blame), decompilation of compiled binaries, or unauthorized repository access. This provides direct access to SQL Server databases with full read/write capabilities, ability to execute stored procedures, modify schemas, and potentially escalate to SA (system administrator) privileges. Hardcoded passwords violate security best practices and compliance requirements (PCI DSS, HIPAA, SOC 2, ISO 27001). IMMEDIATE ACTIONS: 1) Remove hardcoded password from source code immediately, 2) Rotate SQL Server credentials using ALTER LOGIN statements, 3) Store credentials in secure vaults: Azure Key Vault (for Azure-hosted apps), AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, CyberArk, or encrypted environment variables that are not committed to source control, 4) Review git commit history and remove sensitive data using git-filter-branch or BFG Repo-Cleaner, 5) Implement Windows Integrated Authentication where possible (eliminates password storage), 6) Use Managed Identity for Azure SQL or IAM roles for AWS RDS, 7) Enable SQL Server audit logging for authentication events, 8) Implement code scanning in CI/CD pipelines to prevent future credential commits.",
